Reading in the data

deviating a little here from the tutorial -- reading in our data from hise instead of with pooch, so we use hisepy.cache_files().

In[2]:
import hisepy

samples = {
    "s1d1": "8c4c7e50-4888-4d98-901b-b9356056d1b8",
    "s1d3": "4d420fd6-c2a3-4d96-a6cf-1a2d717c95f4",
}
adatas = {}

for sample_id, uuid in samples.items():
    path = hisepy.cache_files([uuid])[0]
    sample_adata = sc.read_10x_h5(path)
    sample_adata.var_names_make_unique()
    adatas[sample_id] = sample_adata

adata = ad.concat(adatas, label="sample")
adata.obs_names_make_unique()
print(adata.obs["sample"].value_counts())
adata

Quality control

We will be calculating the quality control metrics with calculate_qc_metrics() (shocker) but first, we have to assign some groups which we can pass into that.

In[3]:
# mitochondrial genes, "MT-" for human, "Mt-" for mouse
adata.var["mt"] = adata.var_names.str.startswith("MT-")
# ribosomal genes
adata.var["ribo"] = adata.var_names.str.startswith(("RPS", "RPL"))
# hemoglobin genes
adata.var["hb"] = adata.var_names.str.contains("^HB[^(P)]")

and now we can calculate the metrics..

In[4]:
sc.pp.calculate_qc_metrics(
    adata, qc_vars=["mt", "ribo", "hb"], inplace=True, log1p=True
)

Now we can take a look at some of the quality control metrics

In[5]:

In[6]:
sc.pl.scatter(adata, "total_counts", "n_genes_by_counts", color="pct_counts_mt")

From the tutorial:

Based on the QC metric plots, one could now remove cells that have too many mitochondrial genes expressed or too many total counts by setting manual or automatic thresholds. However, sometimes what appears to be poor QC metrics can be driven by real biology so we suggest starting with a very permissive filtering strategy and revisiting it at a later point. We therefore now only filter cells with less than 100 genes expressed and genes that are detected in less than 3 cells.

Additionally, it is important to note that for datasets with multiple batches, quality control should be performed for each sample individually as quality control thresholds can vary substantially between batches.

Why filter out things with too many mitochondrial genes? -- looks like this could potentially be due to cells dying/in stress -- mitochondria may still be intact, meaning that more mitochondrial dna is still around than nuclear.

Normalization

Now onto normalization.

From the tutorial:

The next preprocessing step is normalization. A common approach is count depth scaling with subsequent log plus one (log1p) transformation. Count depth scaling normalizes the data to a size factor such as the median count depth in the dataset, ten thousand (CP10k) or one million (CPM, counts per million). The size factor for count depth scaling can be controlled via target_sum in pp.normalize_total. We are applying median count depth normalization with log1p transformation (AKA log1PF).

From 10X genomics:

The size-factor normalization reduces the technical variation from sequencing depth, while the log transformation minimizes the effects from expression outliers and helps prevent high-abundance genes from dominating downstream analysis due to their higher technical variability.

However, this can lead to some biases and makes some assumptions that aren't necessarily the best. More options are listed in the 10x Genomics link above, but they all are in R. Should check in at our meeting to see if it is worth exploring other options for this.

In[10]:
# Saving count data
adata.layers["counts"] = adata.X.copy()
In[11]:
# Normalizing to median total counts
sc.pp.normalize_total(adata)
# Logarithmize the data
sc.pp.log1p(adata)

Nearest neighbors/UMAP time

Alright.. I don't really understand UMAP all that well so I took a look at this interactive explanation.

Essentially we are building a graph of probability that data points are connected. This is done by taking points, and finding the nth nearest neighbors based on a distance and n. Some additional things:

  • The likelihood that two points are connected decreases with an increased radius
  • Each point must be in contact with at least its nearest neighbor -- keeps balance of local vs global structure

Then, a low-dimension analogue is optimized (stochastically). Don't really get how. The paper is comparing UMAP to t-SNE but that doesn't really help since I don't know what that is. Oh.. looks like it's essentially using KL divergence as the metric for optimization? I think I presented on this a few years ago for a math class but I have since forgotten the details.. essential it's statistical distance measuring entropy between two distributions.

Important to remember here is that we've got two hyperparameters which seriously shape how this gets processed down the line which need tuning:

  • number of neighbors (most important)
  • distance

Anyways... here's how to do it (using default parameters -- n_neighbors = 15 in sc.pp.neigbors(), min_dist = 0.5 in sc.tl.umap()).

In[21]:
# start with getting the neighbors graph
sc.pp.neighbors(adata)
In[22]:
# and umaping it
sc.tl.umap(adata)
In[23]:
# and now plotting it
sc.pl.umap(
    adata,
    color="sample",
    # Setting a smaller point size to get prevent overlap
    size=2,
)

Looks like there is a small batch effect here, but nothing to worry about. If it is something to worry about down the road, the tutorial recommends scanorama and scvi-tools for batch correction/integration.

Clustering

Seems like they recommend the Leiden graph-clustering method.. should look into this to see more about how it works, but it operates based off of the neighborhood graph we already made.

In[32]:
# Using the igraph implementation and a fixed number of iterations can be significantly faster, especially for larger datasets
sc.tl.leiden(adata, flavor="igraph", n_iterations=2)
In[33]:
# and plotting it
sc.pl.umap(adata, color=["leiden"])
